XmlSerializer doesn't encode/escape Unicode characters (e.g. German quotation marks as illustrated below) during serialization when TextWriter with non-Unicode encoding e.g. ISO-8859-1 is used. I've tested this behavior on .NET Framework 4.5.2, 4.7.2 and .NET Core 2.2.

Since mentioned characters are part of Unicode and are not known to ISO-8859-1 the expected behavior would be the same as when using XmlWriter so encoding the characters with their character entity references. I understand this would be a breaking change so probably this issue will get closed but perhaps someone will find this helpful in future.

Execution of the following code results in incorrect XML and consequently deserialization exception:

```
public class Foo
{
    [XmlAttribute("bar")]
    public string Bar { get; set; } = new string(new[]
    {
        '\u201A', // ‚ replaced with 44 ,
        '\u2018', // ‘ replaced with 39 '
        '\u201E', // „ replaced with 34 "
        '\u201C'  // “ replaced with 34 "
    });
}

var iso88591 = Encoding.GetEncoding("ISO-8859-1");
var ms = new MemoryStream();
var sw = new StreamWriter(ms, iso88591);
var sr = new StreamReader(ms, iso88591);
var serializer = new XmlSerializer(typeof(Foo));

serializer.Serialize(sw, new Foo());
var charPreview = iso88591.GetString(ms.GetBuffer()).ToCharArray();
ms.Position = 0;
serializer.Deserialize(sr); //fails due containing extra quotation marks
```

The workaround would be to use Serialize method overload accepting XmlWriter e.g.:
```
var xmlWriter = XmlWriter.Create(ms, new XmlWriterSettings() { Encoding = iso88591 });
serializer.Serialize(xmlWriter, new Foo());
```

